#vectorizing the data
import numpy as np

def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension=10000):
    # Create an all-zero matrix of shape (len(sequences), dimension)
    results = np.zeros((len(sequences), dimension))
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        results[i, sequence] = 1.  # set specific indices of results[i] to 1s
    return results

# Our vectorized training data
x_train = vectorize_sequences(train_data)
# Our vectorized test data
x_test = vectorize_sequences(test_data)

from keras import models
from keras import layers

model_one_hidden_layer = models.Sequential()
model_one_hidden_layer.add(layers.Dense(32, activation='relu', input_shape=(10000,)))
model_one_hidden_layer.add(layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

model_one_hidden_layer.compile(optimizer="rmsprop",
                               loss="binary_crossentropy",
                               metrics=["accuracy"])

x_val = x_train[:10000]
partial_x_train = x_train[10000:]

y_val = y_train[:10000]
partial_y_train = y_train[10000:]

history_one_hidden_layer = model_one_hidden_layer.fit(partial_x_train,
                                                      partial_y_train,
                                                      epochs=20,
                                                      batch_size=512,
                                                      validation_data=(x_val, y_val))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
def plot_history(history):
    history_dict = history.history
    loss_values = history_dict["loss"]
    val_loss_values = history_dict["val_loss"]
    epochs = range(1, len(loss_values) + 1)

    plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, "bo", label="Training loss")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, "b", label="Validation loss")
    plt.title("Training and validation loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    plt.clf()
    acc = history_dict["accuracy"]
    val_acc = history_dict["val_accuracy"]

    plt.plot(epochs, acc, "bo", label="Training acc")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc, "b", label="Validation acc")
    plt.title("Training and validation accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

from keras import regularizers
model_regularization_dropout = models.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(32, activation="tanh", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)),
    layers.Dropout(0.5),
    layers.Dense(32, activation="tanh", kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)),
    layers.Dropout(0.5),
    layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")])

Summary:

In this exercise, various neural network configurations on the IMDB dataset have been applied- modifying the number of hidden layers, hidden units, activation functions, and loss functions. However, despite using regularization techniques such as L2 regularization and Dropout, the model displayed signs of overfitting after several epochs, where the validation accuracy stagnated, and the loss increased.

From the graphs it is observed that--

  1. Fewer Hidden Units (16 units):
  • Achieved high training accuracy, reaching nearly 100% by the end of training.
  • However, validation accuracy stagnated around 87%, while validation loss increased significantly towards the end. This indicates potential overfitting, where the model performs well on the training data but generalizes poorly to new data.
  1. More Hidden Units (64 units):
  • This model also reached 100% training accuracy.
  • Validation accuracy was relatively stable, fluctuating around 87%. However, validation loss increased as the epochs progressed, suggesting overfitting similar to the model with fewer hidden units.
  1. Using MSE Loss Function Instead of Binary Cross-Entropy:
  • This model's performance was slightly different in terms of loss values due to the change in the loss function.
  • The validation accuracy was comparable to the models using binary cross-entropy, reaching around 87-88%, with validation loss hovering at reasonable levels (though slightly worse than the binary cross-entropy model).
  1. Using Tanh Activation Instead of Relu:
  • The model using the tanh activation achieved good accuracy with a comparable performance to the relu models.
  • Validation accuracy and loss values were similar, indicating that switching the activation function did not drastically impact performance in this case.

Overall, models with fewer and more hidden units performed similarly, with no drastic improvement from having more hidden units, though all suffered from overfitting. The MSE loss model showed slightly worse performance compared to binary cross-entropy, while the tanh activation model performed on par with the relu model.
